      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "IMRC's impact is characterized by its multi-sectoral approach to poverty alleviation. In 2021 alone, the organization supported <cite id=\"15\">16,493 students</cite> and treated <cite id=\"16\">183,100 patients</cite> through its healthcare initiatives. This scale is supported by a <cite id=\"17\">100% independent board of directors</cite>, which provides strong oversight for its <cite id=\"18\">$48.7 million asset base</cite>."
      ],
      "summary": "Founded in <cite id=\"1\">1981</cite>, Indian Muslim Relief and Charities (IMRC) is a dedicated humanitarian organization focused on empowering India\u2019s marginalized minorities through <cite id=\"2\">healthcare, education, and social security programs</cite>. The organization operates with a massive scale of impact, having provided <cite id=\"3\">over 16 million meals</cite> and treated <cite id=\"4\">30,000 patients</cite> in a single reporting year. IMRC maintains a lean operational model, reporting <cite id=\"5\">$13,833,809 in total revenue</cite> for 2023 while achieving <cite id=\"6\">extraordinary fundraising efficiency</cite> by spending only <cite id=\"7\">$0.01 to raise every $1</cite>. The organization is deeply rooted in Islamic philanthropic traditions, maintaining <cite id=\"8\">verified zakat eligibility</cite> and serving all eight asnaf categories, including the <cite id=\"9\">poor (fuqara) and needy (masakin)</cite>. Despite its high program efficiency, IMRC currently holds <cite id=\"10\">$48.7 million in net assets</cite>, representing a significant reserve of <cite id=\"11\">55.7 months of working capital</cite>. This financial stability ensures long-term sustainability but suggests a high capacity for <cite id=\"12\">increased program deployment</cite> to address the urgent needs of underserved populations in India.",
